{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f7364b3f-70fc-4b45-b642-6f1f62c16b49","content":"To switch from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform, you just need to **remove** (or set to `false`) the `<UseVSTest>` property in your project file:\n\n```xml\n<!-- Before -->\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n\n<!-- After -->\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n</Project>\n```\n\n**Why this is enough:** Starting with MSTest.Sdk **3.4+**, Microsoft.Testing.Platform is the **default** runner. Setting `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` was explicitly opting out of it. Removing that property (or setting it to `false`) enables the new platform automatically.\n\n**Key behavior changes to be aware of:**\n\n| Area | Change |\n|---|---|\n| **CLI** | Use `dotnet test` as before, but you can also run the test executable directly (`./MyTests.exe`) |\n| **`--filter`** | Still supported, but the syntax is now `--filter \"Name=MyTest\"` when running the exe directly |\n| **Output** | Console output format changes; use `--report-trx` to get TRX reports |\n| **CI/IDE** | VS 2022 17.10+ and `dotnet test` work seamlessly; older VS versions may need the VSTest bridge |\n\nIf you rely on `.runsettings`, those are still supported. No other project changes are needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"10123206-6407-4789-908e-ccc139846a4c","outputTokens":373,"requestId":"042B:29B12:1F50A07:23236EA:69E81A8D"},"id":"5fa0d9c9-c37d-4997-8d12-bfb3d233c076","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:47:19.904Z","parentId":"d10c1c1d-b195-4a25-87a3-8f8883e68d3e"}
